				 Lawyers boycott high court
 OUR LEGAL REPORTER																								Calcutta, Nov 15: The Calcutta High Court bar association has decided to stage a boycott until the judgment in the March 14 firing case is delivered.																								The lawyers informed Chief Justice S.S. Nijjar of their decision minutes after the court reopened today after a month-long vacation. They told Nijjar that the violence in Nandigram on November 9 and 10 could have been avoided had the judgment come in time.																								The chief justice said the verdict would be delivered tomorrow, but the lawyers were not convinced. We will not budge an inch from our decision to boycott the court until the judgment is delivered, Uttam Majumdar, a former bar association secretary, said.																								Over 1,000 lawyers then marched to Raj Bhavan, shouting slogans against the armed recapture of Nandigram villages. A 10-member delegation from the association later met governor Gopal Krishna Gandhi and handed him a memorandum demanding action against the guilty.
